{
  "texts": [
    "This assumption is supported by our discussion of background charges in section 2.3.3.",
    "The locations of the zeroes of ξ + (z) are given by {z * a } (we know from appendix D that a = 1,... N Γ such that M = N Γ) and we denote the zeroes of η + (z) by {t k } for some label k. These provide the possible locations for the \"hidden poles\" of ∂φ(z).",
    "However, as we will now show, the {t k } do not in fact give rise to poles in ∂φ(z).We learn from (5.6) thatF ∂ΦJ + (z) = F η + ∂ξ + (z) -F U J + (z).The fields U and J + can be viewed independently in the path integral, so we can use the same intuition as above to justifyF U J + (t k) = F U J + (z * a) = 0, since these points correspond to zeroes of F J + (z).",
    "Note that U is a conformal tensor contained in the free field realisation, so it will not have any poles away from insertion points to counteract these zeroes of F J + (z).",
    "32 Moreover, we can deduce that F η + ∂ξ + (z) has a zero whenever η + → 0, such that F η + ∂ξ + (t k) = 0 for all k. Overall, we find that F ∂ΦJ + (t k) = F ∂Φ (t k)F J + (t k) = 0, such that there is no pole in ∂φ(z) at the points t k.By contrast, whilst F U J + (z * a) = 0, this is not the case for F η + ∂ξ + (z * a), leading to hidden poles of ∂φ(z)."
  ]
}